cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.MM, cs.CR, cs.SI 

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as it presents results from an extensive LTE measurement campaign in Dublin, Ireland using a custom performance measurement tool. The paper also discusses the characteristics of link layer RTT and bandwidth vs link signal strength, which are important aspects of networking and internet architecture. 

The paper could also belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory) as it discusses the performance of LTE/4G networks, which involves the transmission and processing of information. 

Additionally, the paper could be categorized under cs.MM (Multimedia) as LTE/4G networks are specifically designed to improve the network performance for data traffic, which includes multimedia applications such as video streaming and online gaming. 

The paper could also be classified under cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as LTE/4G networks involve the transmission of sensitive information and require secure communication protocols. 

Finally, the paper could belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it discusses the performance of LTE/4G networks in a specific location (Dublin, Ireland) and for mobile users on public transport within the city, which involves social and information networks.
